    <!-- Content sections -->
    <mj-section css-class="mj_section" background-color="#ffffff">
      <mj-column>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopolitics.world/email/images/gp-nov-26-3.jpg" alt="Which countries have nuclear weapons? " href="https://www.geopolitics.world" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Nine countries possess nuclear weapons for security, deterrence, and influence. The <a href="https://disarmament.unoda.org/wmd/nuclear/npt/" target="_blank">NPT</a> recognizes five nuclear states: the U.S., Russia, China, France, and the UK. These nations developed arsenals during World War II and the Cold War to deter aggression, maintain power, and safeguard allies. The U.S. and Russia lead with the largest arsenals, prioritizing global dominance.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Outside the NPT, India and Pakistan pursued weapons to counter regional rivals, while Israel (undeclared) maintains nuclear ambiguity for existential security. North Korea developed nuclear weapons for regime survival and deterrence.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;"> Countries develop nuclear weapons to deter threats, ensure strategic independence, and assert status, particularly in volatile regions. Global efforts like the NPT, <a href="https://www.ctbto.org/our-mission/the-treaty" target="_blank">CTBT</a>, and bilateral treaties like <a href="https://www.britannica.com/event/Strategic-Arms-Reduction-Talks" target="_blank">START</a> aim to limit proliferation. Still, disarmament remains challenging due to geopolitical tensions and reliance on nuclear arsenals for national security. Nuclear weapons continue to symbolize power and protection.​</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
